IActionResult in ASP.NET Core is an interface that represents the result of an action method in a controller. It allows you to return different types of responses (like views, JSON, status codes, or redirects) in a unified way, making your controller methods flexible and consistent.

üåê What is IActionResult?
Definition: IActionResult is part of the Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc namespace. It defines a contract for action results that a controller action can return.
Purpose: It abstracts the response so you can return various result types (e.g., Ok(), NotFound(), Redirect(), View()) without tying your method to a specific return type.
Why Use IActionResult?
Flexibility: You can return different responses depending on conditions. For example:

csharp
public IActionResult GetProduct(int id)
{
    var product = _context.Products.Find(id);
    if (product == null)
        return NotFound();
    return Ok(product);
}
Consistency: Keeps controller methods uniform, especially in APIs where you may need to return success, error, or redirect responses.

Extensibility: You can create custom action results by implementing IActionResult.

üîë Common Implementations of IActionResult
OkResult ‚Üí Returns HTTP 200 (success).

NotFoundResult ‚Üí Returns HTTP 404 (resource not found).

BadRequestResult ‚Üí Returns HTTP 400 (invalid request).

RedirectResult ‚Üí Redirects to another URL.

ViewResult ‚Üí Returns a Razor view in MVC.

JsonResult ‚Üí Returns JSON data.

IActionResult vs ActionResult<T>
IActionResult: Non-generic, can return any type of result.

ActionResult<T>: Generic, combines strong typing with flexibility. For example:

csharp
public ActionResult<Product> GetProduct(int id)
{
    var product = _context.Products.Find(id);
    if (product == null)
        return NotFound();
    return product; // Automatically wrapped in OkObjectResult
}
This is often preferred in Web APIs for clarity and type safety.

